The inventor of the World Wide Web is planning to launch a New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a new company that seeks to rival with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's Solid-Free Platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored as well as people who are allowed access to such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee stated by joking that Inrupt was intended to "lord the world."
"We must do it now," he said about the launch.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to enable people to create their own "online personal data store" or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a musical library, as well as other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on one browser.
The particularity of the personal data store online is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what kind of information.
The company calls this "personal responsibility through data".
According to the company's CEO, John Bruce, the idea of Inrupt is that the company brings appropriate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
