The study of the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Western Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key places around the property to monitor the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bats and the activities of different species.
A map and report on habitat will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of prairies and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other associated species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the perchours and results in the loss of their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as bite-killing papers and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as company cat attacks.
The bats aren't really blind.
