Point information on red tide: Low concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in concentrations of the red tide in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - causing fear of decreasing concentrations.
The red tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in less sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or off, medium concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations in Lee County and off of Lee County, high concentrations at the bottom or wide in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation was reported in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
